title: Correct Tier 2 soil model UI for source removal BMPs
body: Presently, the source removal BMP tab in the Tier 2 soil model UI does not have a button to turn off or on this type of BMP.  There are 5 types of source removal BMPs.  The user must cycle through each one to ensure they are all unchecked and that there is zero soil removal to ensure there are NO source removal BMPs.  A check box needs to be added to the main source removal BMP screen to turn off all or turn on all source removal BMPs.  If turned on, the user must then cycle through each one to enter inputs or leave as zero.  The soil model pre-processor needs to be corrected to check if source removal BMPs are off or on, and the set the input flag accordingly so the soil model does not needlessly execute source removal processes when they are not even turned on.

title: WFF Surface Water and Aquifer Percent Plus Operator
body:
Not to be confused with the WFF Surface Water and Aquifer Plus Operator in which the user inputs groundwater flow rate to surface water, this percent version is supposed to allow the user to input a fraction, percent, or tenths of total groundwater flow rate that discharges to surface water.  The UI will not accept %, but does except fraction.  If you select percent and try to enter a value, you will get an error message and the units are changed back to fraction.  If you enter a fraction, the UI may or may not work.  

After more thought, the best fix is to add the percent and fraction options that are in this module to the other WFF Surface Water and Aquifer Plus Operator, and remove this Percent module.  That way, the user can choose among flow rate, percent, or fraction of groundwater flow discharging to surface water.  There also needs to be a check in the UI to prevent the user from specifying a flow rate that is larger than the available groundwater flow rate at the location of discharge (i.e., where the Plus Operator is combining flows).  This flow rate is easily determined from the WFF file (aquifer section) entering the module.  Of course, if there is more than one WFF with aquifer fluxes entering the module, a summation will be required.  This may require modifying the module code as well as the UI.  The modified Plus Operator will require testing.

There will also be a need to modify the new Arctic Input Helper tool, its help file, and the Arctic Application Info Help file to explain that there are three options for entering the required input for the new WFF Surface Water and Aquifer Plus Operator. The tool also needs to have a note on the screen explaining that the user can also enter percent or fraction of groundwater flow or the flow rate displayed by the tool.  All this will need to be tested (i.e., using flow, percent, fraction) in the Arctic test case.

Health Benchmarks Database (CR 2)
body: Develop a new database for human and ecological protective health benchmarks (i.e., comparison values, or CVs) that are based on risk-based concentrations (RBCs) utilizing various existing Web-based databases.  Ensure that FRESCO allows the user to change site and application specific CVs within their application to customized, local (e.g., state regulated) values that could be different from those in the FRESCO Benchmark Database.  This UI feature should also include referencing the source of user supplied CVs.  Ensure that values in the FRESCO Benchmark Database include information regarding the source of the values.  Attempt to develop a CV import tool (i.e., DCE) (or at least Web links to on-line reliable sources of benchmarks) knowing that they are updated quarterly in some on-line databases and there needs to be a capability to import new values.  THIS TASK INCLUDES TWO FUNCTIONALITY TASKS IN THE REQUIREMENTS REPORT.
